WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
You just came back from your first holiday in quite a while.

00:05.000 --> 00:10.000
Well, my first holiday of, let's say, three weeks or more in quite a while.

00:10.000 --> 00:11.000
How was that?

00:11.000 --> 00:13.000
Astounding.

00:13.000 --> 00:21.000
Really very good to see what's going on in the rest of the world at this particular moment.

00:21.000 --> 00:26.000
We had previously gone to India in the year to visit family.

00:26.000 --> 00:32.000
This was to go back to Turkey and to go to Portugal, but also to the Azores Islands.

00:32.000 --> 00:39.000
I can't tell you how meaningful it was for me to be back traveling.

00:39.000 --> 00:40.000
Why?

00:40.000 --> 00:44.000
Well, I mean, partially it's reacquaint.

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
When you have children and children change your game for about two decades,

00:48.000 --> 00:51.000
you have to realize that that's a transient period.

00:51.000 --> 00:54.000
It felt like it was going to go on forever.

00:54.000 --> 00:59.000
This was sort of trying to figure out what is it like to go from traveling in your 20s and 30s with that kids

00:59.000 --> 01:05.000
to traveling with your kids at the last moment that you still have them at home.

01:05.000 --> 01:08.000
Now you're going to have the rest of your life without them again,

01:08.000 --> 01:12.000
but you can't go back to backpacking and doing certain other things that were easy for you.

01:12.000 --> 01:17.000
You have to figure out how to rejoin your previous life that has been in progress without you actually.

01:17.000 --> 01:18.000
Ending for a long time.

01:18.000 --> 01:19.000
Exactly.

01:19.000 --> 01:21.000
That's sabbatical from life almost.

01:21.000 --> 01:24.000
Another thing is that you forget about parts of yourself.

01:24.000 --> 01:34.000
I forgot that I spoke Turkish not well, but I spoke rudimentary Tarzan Turkish 30 years ago.

01:34.000 --> 01:41.000
To be back in Istanbul and suddenly have words and phrases and things come back

01:41.000 --> 01:46.000
and be talking to cab drivers and just people in the street seeing the change.

01:46.000 --> 01:50.000
Obviously, there's been an enormous amount of change in Turkey.

01:50.000 --> 01:55.000
Portugal is fascinating seeing certain things at the end of their life cycle.

01:55.000 --> 02:00.000
We were at a synagogue in Bursa where the home of the Ottoman Empire,

02:00.000 --> 02:05.000
where they were down to their last 50 people, which is a common enough thing

02:05.000 --> 02:11.000
when we visit diaspora Jewish communities at the tail end with the embers still glowing hot

02:11.000 --> 02:14.000
but no chance for a rebirth.

02:14.000 --> 02:23.000
Then in the Azores, I was not prepared for the level of beauty that we encountered.

02:23.000 --> 02:29.000
There is a level of beauty that I've only experienced two, maybe three times in my life

02:29.000 --> 02:34.000
that sort of leaves you physically sick, like ill.

02:34.000 --> 02:38.000
It's so beautiful that your body is the weak link.

02:38.000 --> 02:42.000
You might think that sugar is tasty, but if you were to eat a bag of sugar,

02:42.000 --> 02:44.000
you'd probably be sick to your stomach.

02:44.000 --> 02:51.000
I would say this was so much beauty that it was at an almost pathological level

02:51.000 --> 02:56.000
and more than I think my family could really take in.

02:56.000 --> 02:57.000
We're just so moving.

02:57.000 --> 03:01.000
I've heard you say before about how a lot of the time you don't realize

03:01.000 --> 03:04.000
the last time you're going to do a thing with a person.

03:04.000 --> 03:08.000
A lot of friends, especially ones that are fathers, have told me the same thing.

03:08.000 --> 03:10.000
The last time that you'll bounce your daughter on your knee.

03:10.000 --> 03:12.000
You don't know when it's going to happen, but it's going to happen.

03:12.000 --> 03:16.000
There's also a really strange realization when you get deeper into adulthood

03:16.000 --> 03:19.000
and work out that probably by the age of 18 or 20,

03:19.000 --> 03:24.000
you've spent 97 or 98% of the time you're going to spend with your parents.

03:24.000 --> 03:27.000
All that you wanted for the last four years was to be away from them

03:27.000 --> 03:31.000
and now all that you want is to have a little bit more time and it's all gone

03:31.000 --> 03:32.000
and you squandered it while it was there.

03:32.000 --> 03:34.000
I'm on the ethnic program.

03:34.000 --> 03:36.000
We don't believe in this stuff.

03:37.000 --> 03:40.000
My children don't become adults at the age of 18.

03:40.000 --> 03:44.000
I don't care about the laws of the United States or the state of California.

03:44.000 --> 03:47.000
I think we do family wrong in the States.

03:47.000 --> 03:51.000
You send them off to college and then you tell them,

03:51.000 --> 03:56.000
go follow your dream and they bounce into some locality that you aren't in

03:56.000 --> 03:59.000
and you don't get the benefit of these very strong families

03:59.000 --> 04:03.000
because the market has been so strong in the US for so long.

04:03.000 --> 04:07.000
And the market more or less took over all sorts of duties

04:07.000 --> 04:09.000
that were assigned to families historically.

04:09.000 --> 04:11.000
And so the reason that people always say,

04:11.000 --> 04:15.000
oh, your families are weak was because our markets were strong, right?

04:15.000 --> 04:18.000
And so insurance and opportunity,

04:18.000 --> 04:24.000
all of these things that could be handed over to the market were.

04:24.000 --> 04:28.000
And as a result, when we find out that the markets are not safe,

04:28.000 --> 04:32.000
we realize that we've abandoned the structures that we needed to retreat to

04:32.000 --> 04:36.000
that our families are quite small, below replacement rate very often.

04:36.000 --> 04:38.000
And we don't live in the same place.

04:38.000 --> 04:40.000
And so, you know, I married a woman from India

04:40.000 --> 04:44.000
and I basically carry a lot of Eastern European norms.

04:44.000 --> 04:47.000
And so my feeling is that my children are my children forever.

04:47.000 --> 04:49.000
And I'm not letting go of them.

04:49.000 --> 04:53.000
And this idea that it's your life and you can do what you want

04:53.000 --> 04:55.000
is only true up to a point.

04:55.000 --> 04:57.000
You also have a continuity issue.

04:57.000 --> 04:59.000
And this is normal, by the way.

04:59.000 --> 05:03.000
And it may sound weird in an American context,

05:03.000 --> 05:06.000
but I think that the world recognizes that we're links in a chain

05:06.000 --> 05:09.000
and there's a certain amount that you get to do that's just yours

05:09.000 --> 05:13.000
because it's your life, but never go full Billy Joel.

05:13.000 --> 05:14.000
Yeah.

