Pan-generational housing is something being in Austin,

05:17.000 --> 05:20.000
people getting ranches, starting even commune,

05:20.000 --> 05:23.000
you know, 10 family mini villages with a bunch of other people.

05:23.000 --> 05:24.000
Yeah.

05:24.000 --> 05:27.000
It's something that I'm seeing occur more and more.

05:27.000 --> 05:32.000
And, you know, in an atomized, like mass solipsism,

05:32.000 --> 05:35.000
mass individualism society, this doesn't sound like a bad redress.

05:35.000 --> 05:36.000
We got to the end of it.

05:36.000 --> 05:38.000
We got to the end of that dream.

05:38.000 --> 05:41.000
And it didn't work.

05:41.000 --> 05:44.000
You've been around a lot of very powerful, very rich people

05:44.000 --> 05:45.000
throughout your career.

05:45.000 --> 05:46.000
No, no, that's not true.

05:46.000 --> 05:49.000
Only relatively recently, only in the last decade and a half.

05:49.000 --> 05:52.000
That's quite a while in many people's lives.

05:52.000 --> 06:00.000
What do you think that most normal people would be surprised to know

06:00.000 --> 06:06.000
about the powerful and the rich individuals, world views,

06:06.000 --> 06:09.000
the way that they hold themselves, what is and isn't true?

06:09.000 --> 06:13.000
They feel powerless.

06:13.000 --> 06:19.000
That's one of the craziest things is that very often you're at a table

06:19.000 --> 06:25.000
of people of immeasurable wealth and they're talking about the rich

06:25.000 --> 06:27.000
or the hyper-connected.

06:27.000 --> 06:30.000
They don't see themselves in these terms.

06:30.000 --> 06:31.000
Why?

06:31.000 --> 06:34.000
I think there's different kinds of rich, to be honest.

06:34.000 --> 06:42.000
I think that if, for example, you got rich from, let's say, arms manufacturing,

06:42.000 --> 06:46.000
you've been entwined with government your whole life or agriculture,

06:46.000 --> 06:53.000
something that's highly regulated that extraction oil and gas.

06:53.000 --> 06:57.000
Those people, I think, have always been close to power.

06:57.000 --> 07:01.000
A lot of the dream of tech, for example, was we don't need the government.

07:01.000 --> 07:06.000
We'll just build stuff in our garages and if it's cool, it'll take care of itself.

07:06.000 --> 07:11.000
And therefore, we're minimally dependent on the traditional ecosystems.

07:11.000 --> 07:16.000
So a lot of tech money felt disenfranchised.

07:16.000 --> 07:19.000
They didn't know how to play the game.

07:19.000 --> 07:23.000
That was both to its credit and a huge danger.

07:23.000 --> 07:27.000
But I think one of the things that I find very interesting is that when people are

07:27.000 --> 07:34.000
not rate-limited by money, they're rate-limited by all sorts of other things.

07:34.000 --> 07:37.000
They may not want their number to go down.

07:37.000 --> 07:42.000
So they go from 6 billion to 4 billion would be a huge blow,

07:42.000 --> 07:47.000
even though it doesn't seem to impact normal things.

07:47.000 --> 07:52.000
Another thing is that most of them have given up on the retail notion of reality.

07:52.000 --> 07:58.000
Whatever mainstream media, if you have a worldview that allows you to listen

07:58.000 --> 08:04.000
to national public radio that then reads the Wall Street Journal

08:04.000 --> 08:08.000
and The Times and The New Yorker, whatever that point of view is,

08:08.000 --> 08:16.000
most of the very powerful rich people I know have checked out at a level that is astounding.

08:16.000 --> 08:22.000
They don't believe that they can afford to depend on normal institutions.

08:22.000 --> 08:24.000
How does that show up in their lives?

08:24.000 --> 08:26.000
Weird ways.

08:26.000 --> 08:28.000
They don't have a regular doctor.

08:28.000 --> 08:30.000
They have concierge medicine.

08:30.000 --> 08:35.000
Their fire policy comes with a private fire department that will fight for their home

08:35.000 --> 08:38.000
but won't necessarily fight for homes next door unless it's just-

08:38.000 --> 08:41.000
I didn't know that that was a thing, okay?

08:41.000 --> 08:46.000
You know, it's not until you travel with some of these people

08:46.000 --> 08:50.000
that you realize that there's a secret corridor in the airport

08:50.000 --> 08:52.000
or a way of getting onto the plane.

08:52.000 --> 08:57.000
There's a lot of infrastructure built for a very small number of people.

08:58.000 --> 09:02.000
For the most part, they can't figure out what to do with the money.

09:02.000 --> 09:04.000
It's my belief.

09:07.000 --> 09:10.000
If you believe that the world is headed towards an apocalypse,

09:10.000 --> 09:13.000
you're very unlikely to want to contribute money

09:13.000 --> 09:17.000
because that's the only fungible thing you have in an emergency.

09:17.000 --> 09:22.000
I think that a lot of the sort of apocalyptic thinking of very powerful people

09:22.000 --> 09:27.000
is very destructive because they're trying to figure out

09:27.000 --> 09:30.000
how to survive a mild apocalypse,

09:30.000 --> 09:32.000
like a six months of your-

09:32.000 --> 09:35.000
You know, if I have six months of canned goods

09:35.000 --> 09:43.000
and I've got four X Navy SEALs on my property in a remote location in Montana,

09:43.000 --> 09:46.000
can I weather the storm with a few diesel generators?

09:46.000 --> 09:51.000
So if it's a very mild apocalypse, maybe they've got six months' plan.

09:52.000 --> 09:55.000
But I think that there's a lot of thinking

09:55.000 --> 09:59.000
that you should husband your resources because you don't know what's coming

09:59.000 --> 10:01.000
given that things are going to have to collapse.

10:01.000 --> 10:06.000
And I think it's very sad because those are the people who could shore up the system.

10:07.000 --> 10:12.000
It's interesting to think about helplessness at the top end of the wealth distribution

10:12.000 --> 10:17.000
given that a lot of people feel like they are restricted by their material possessions.

10:17.000 --> 10:20.000
But it seems like despite there being a lot of abundance,

10:20.000 --> 10:24.000
at least monetarily, the scarcity mentality scales all the way up.

10:24.000 --> 10:25.000
It really does.

10:25.000 --> 10:28.000
And particularly if you've been deprived early in your life,

10:28.000 --> 10:32.000
there's something that happens where you're nervous till your dying day

10:32.000 --> 10:35.000
that you're going to die under an overpass, right?

10:35.000 --> 10:37.000
I'm not kidding.

